      "text": "YouTube (Video Streaming)\n\nFunctional Requirements -\n   1. Users can upload videos\n   2. Users can stream videos\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. Videos of 128GB in size should be uploaded in a resumable manner.\n   2. Videos can be streamed in multiple qualities \n          a. Users with low bandwidth will watch video in 360p quality.\n          b. Users with high bandwidth can watch video in 1080p quality\n   3. The video latency at the beginning should be < 500 ms irrespective of quality to \n       indicate the users that their request is processed. \n   4. The system should prioritize availability\n   5. The upload TPS could be 15 requests/sec, given 1 M uploads per day\n   6. The system should support 12K requests/sec to stream videos.\n   7. The system should not loose any data and should not have single point of failure.\n\nAPI Contracts - \n \n1. Users can upload videos - \n\nPOST /upload/ --> Return pre-signed S3 URL, vidoeId and status code\n\n{\n   userId\n   caption\n   description\n   timestamp\n   originalVideoSize\n   totalRunningTime\n}\n\n2. Users can stream videos -\n\nGET /video/<videoId>?requestedQuality={}\n\n{\n    authorId\n    caption\n    description\n    timestamp\n    runningTime\n    sizeAsPerQuality\n    S3URL (for streaming)\n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Users can upload videos\n      a. App makes a request to Upload microservice to upload a video.\n      b. The Upload microservice persist the information in the DB.\n      c. I will be using S3 as my blob storage.\n      d. The simpler design would be sending small chunks of the video to the\n          Upload microservice so that it can persist to S3 and maintain the progress in the database.\n      e. However, I will not be proceeding with step #d and instead work towards saving the hop \n          by generating a pre-signed S3 URL and return to the App so that it can directly upload the video to S3.\n      f. This design does not cover the use-case when the network is disrupted while uploading\n\n2. Users can stream videos\n      a. Users make a GET request from the Stream microservice and it talks to DB to fetch the requested Video metadata.\n      b. The App constructs the UI with the relevant video metadata and then talks to S3 to stream the video.\n      c. For optimization, I am adding Cloud Front as caching layer before S3.\n\n\n3. Videos can be streamed in multiple qualities \n       a. If a content creation uploads video in 4K and hope it reaches to all parts of the world but majority\n           of the world lives in poor internet coverage and can afford 360 to 720P.\n      b. So the system needs to own the responsibility of generating the video in multiple resolutions, which is \n          long task and need not to be blocked on upload request.\n      c. So, once the upload is complete and the microservice marks the status of Video Metadata as Completed,\n          the actual process of generating the video in different resolution starts (Calls Transcoding)\n     d. Once the data is persisted with status Completed, we can persist the S3 URL and videoId in SQS which is\n         then consumed by Lambda.\n     e. Lambda performs the responsibilities for every new video -\n             a. It downloads the file from S3 and decode the video into its raw form.\n             b. Post that, it creates different resolution of the same video via Sampling and Interpolation.\n             c. Re-encodes the videos of different resolution and uploads to S3.\n             d. It talks to DB and then persist the Information in TranscodedVideo table.\n     f. Now when users with poor internet quality wants to stream the video, the app makes a request with \n        params REQUESTED_QUALITY to Stream microservice which fetches the S3 URL for the requested quality\n        from TranscodedVideo table and the video metadata from Video table and returns to the app.\n    g. The app streams the video from S3 (via CDN) from the given URL.\n\n\n4. Let me explain how streaming works - \n    1. When transcoder (Lambda) decodes the original file and re-encode into different resolution, the lambda \n        breaks them into smaller segments (segmentation) of usually 2 to 5 MB and uploads these segments to the S3.\n    2. Once the segments are uploaded to S3, the lambda persists those list of S3 Link in TranscodedVideo table.\n    3. Now, when the app requests for a certain quality, it fetches the list of S3 URLs, which is around 10ms.\n    4. At this moment, the app does not need to download all the segments from S3 (which will usually be around 20K for a movie of 128GB)\n    5. So, the app downloads segments in a sliding window manner and persist the segment in memory and do not persist in the device storage.\n    6. When the window shifts, it deletes the segments and download new segments. \n    7. As a result, it looks like the app is playing a movie disguised as playing a bunch of smaller segments .\n    8. Now, if the internet quality gets better, the app proactively requests the Stream microservice to fetch a better quality video\n        and skips to downloading those segments of higher quality while playing lower quality video.\n    9. The app keeps a track of last segment downloaded for a lower quality and once the video reaches to that time, the app\n        switches to play the new segment of the higher quality. That's why it looks the video suddenly improved.\n   \nAnother approach - Instead of having TranscodedVideo table, \n   1. we can persist Master Manifest file which contains links of all other resolution manifest file (called Quality-specific Manifest file).\n   2. The Quality-specific Manifest file has the segments name and file location in correct order.\n   3. So, when app requests the Stream microservice, it just provides the master manifest S3 URL location.\n   4. And the app uses the master manifest URL to talk to CDN and S3. So, basically, app becomes the orchestrator instead of the server\n      and directly talks to CDN, preventing a hop. \n\n5. S3 storage and naming convention for these segments - \n     1. I will select videoId as the bucket name\n     2. This will contain the master manifest file and folders for every resolution \n     3. Say we have 3 resolutions -  1080, 720, 360 \n     4. VideoId/1080/1080_manifest_file (Quality Manifest file)\n     5. Inside 1080 folder, you will have 1080_manifest_file and segments folder which will contain all the segment files.\n     6. The 1080_manifest_file will contain the correct order of segment file names and location which needs to be downloaded.\n\n\n6. Videos of 128GB in size should be uploaded in a resumable manner.\n      a. The App uses AWS SDK to strip the 128 GB into multiple small parts of say 5-10MB and persist the chunk information\n          in its local DB.\n      b. When the App first makes a request to the Upload Service, it let it know how many chunks it has the video divided into.\n      c. This is because, the Upload microservice can create a Video Chunk Metadata in its server to avoid single point of failure\n          if the app crashes or even worse the device is eliminated.\n      d. The Upload microservice will talk to S3 to generate UploadId of the multi-part upload and return the S3 URL for all the \n          chunks.\n      e. The App will start uploading to S3 and then make a PATCH request to update the status of that chunk as Complete.\n      f. Now, if the App crashes and it is unable to recover the data from its local DB, it can request the microservice to \n         provide the chunk metadata of the video Id, proceed to upload the chunk from where it left off and continue uploading.\n      g. Once it is completed, the microservice will ask the S3 to mark the multi-upload part as successful and persist the original\n          S3 URL into the Video Table.\n      h. Then it will trigger CDC via SQS and Lambda to get the video transcoded.\n\n7. How would you design your system to allow users to resume watching a video from where they left off, even if they switch devices?\n      a. Whenever an App starts playing a video, it maintains its current activity in ActiveVideoLocal Table with LastModifedTimestamp and LastSyncedTimestamp\n      b. The app makes a periodic request with N seconds to 'SYNC' microservice to sync the data to the ActiveVideo table in the DB. We can also add triggers such as\n          app switch, app close to make a POST/PATCH request to the SYNC microservice before the app goes out of memory.\n      c. Now, when the user left and came back, the app makes a request to get all the user's activities via the Sync microservice. The microservice query the ActiveVideo\n         table and get the list of videoId and lastSegment played and returns to the app.\n     d. Based on videoID, the microservice will query the Video table and get the metadata so that app can start streaming from the last segment played.\n     e. If the same user is watching the same video from 2 different devices, the 'SYNC' microservice would route the requests to 'Conflict Resolution' Server which will\n         validate if the LastSyncedTimestamp (Local) is equal to LastModifiedTimestamp (server). The first checks gives the microservice confidence that both the requests\n         has edits on the latest copy in the server.\n     f. Post that, it validates whose LastModifiedTimestamp (from ActiveVideoLocal) is higher. If one of the requests wins, it will get persisted in the ActiveVideo Table in the server\n     g. The 2nd request will get rejected but to make sure the App which sends the 2nd request has the latest copy, the 'SYNC' microservice will return the latest copy to the \n         2nd App. The 2nd App should take the responsibility to correct its local DB. Meanwhile, the 1st App will not have to do anything as the server and local copy is same.\n     e. Callout: Since this is not about faster retrieval of data (for which I may think about pre-computed cache for user's faster feed), I am only working to get the requirement\n         functionally correct.\n    \n     \n\n\n        \n     \n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "YouTube (Video Streaming)\n\nFunctional Requirements -\n   1. Users can upload videos\n   2. Users can stream videos\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. Videos of 128GB in size should be uploaded in a resumable manner.\n   2. Videos can be streamed in multiple qualities \n          a. Users with low bandwidth will watch video in 360p quality.\n          b. Users with high bandwidth can watch video in 1080p quality\n   3. The video latency at the beginning should be < 500 ms irrespective of quality to \n       indicate the users that their request is processed. \n   4. The system should prioritize availability\n   5. The upload TPS could be 15 requests/sec, given 1 M uploads per day\n   6. The system should support 12K requests/sec to stream videos.\n   7. The system should not loose any data and should not have single point of failure.\n\nAPI Contracts - \n \n1. Users can upload videos - \n\nPOST /upload/ --> Return pre-signed S3 URL, vidoeId and status code\n\n{\n   userId\n   caption\n   description\n   timestamp\n   originalVideoSize\n   totalRunningTime\n}\n\n2. Users can stream videos -\n\nGET /video/<videoId>?requestedQuality={}\n\n{\n    authorId\n    caption\n    description\n    timestamp\n    runningTime\n    sizeAsPerQuality\n    S3URL (for streaming)\n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Users can upload videos\n      a. App makes a request to Upload microservice to upload a video.\n      b. The Upload microservice persist the information in the DB.\n      c. I will be using S3 as my blob storage.\n      d. The simpler design would be sending small chunks of the video to the\n          Upload microservice so that it can persist to S3 and maintain the progress in the database.\n      e. However, I will not be proceeding with step #d and instead work towards saving the hop \n          by generating a pre-signed S3 URL and return to the App so that it can directly upload the video to S3.\n      f. This design does not cover the use-case when the network is disrupted while uploading\n\n2. Users can stream videos\n      a. Users make a GET request from the Stream microservice and it talks to DB to fetch the requested Video metadata.\n      b. The App constructs the UI with the relevant video metadata and then talks to S3 to stream the video.\n      c. For optimization, I am adding Cloud Front as caching layer before S3.\n\n\n3. Videos can be streamed in multiple qualities \n       a. If a content creation uploads video in 4K and hope it reaches to all parts of the world but majority\n           of the world lives in poor internet coverage and can afford 360 to 720P.\n      b. So the system needs to own the responsibility of generating the video in multiple resolutions, which is \n          long task and need not to be blocked on upload request.\n      c. So, once the upload is complete and the microservice marks the status of Video Metadata as Completed,\n          the actual process of generating the video in different resolution starts (Calls Transcoding)\n     d. Once the data is persisted with status Completed, we can persist the S3 URL and videoId in SQS which is\n         then consumed by Lambda.\n     e. Lambda performs the responsibilities for every new video -\n             a. It downloads the file from S3 and decode the video into its raw form.\n             b. Post that, it creates different resolution of the same video via Sampling and Interpolation.\n             c. Re-encodes the videos of different resolution and uploads to S3.\n             d. It talks to DB and then persist the Information in TranscodedVideo table.\n     f. Now when users with poor internet quality wants to stream the video, the app makes a request with \n        params REQUESTED_QUALITY to Stream microservice which fetches the S3 URL for the requested quality\n        from TranscodedVideo table and the video metadata from Video table and returns to the app.\n    g. The app streams the video from S3 (via CDN) from the given URL.\n\n\n4. Let me explain how streaming works - \n    1. When transcoder (Lambda) decodes the original file and re-encode into different resolution, the lambda \n        breaks them into smaller segments (segmentation) of usually 2 to 5 MB and uploads these segments to the S3.\n    2. Once the segments are uploaded to S3, the lambda persists those list of S3 Link in TranscodedVideo table.\n    3. Now, when the app requests for a certain quality, it fetches the list of S3 URLs, which is around 10ms.\n    4. At this moment, the app does not need to download all the segments from S3 (which will usually be around 20K for a movie of 128GB)\n    5. So, the app downloads segments in a sliding window manner and persist the segment in memory and do not persist in the device storage.\n    6. When the window shifts, it deletes the segments and download new segments. \n    7. As a result, it looks like the app is playing a movie disguised as playing a bunch of smaller segments .\n    8. Now, if the internet quality gets better, the app proactively requests the Stream microservice to fetch a better quality video\n        and skips to downloading those segments of higher quality while playing lower quality video.\n    9. The app keeps a track of last segment downloaded for a lower quality and once the video reaches to that time, the app\n        switches to play the new segment of the higher quality. That's why it looks the video suddenly improved.\n   \nAnother approach - Instead of having TranscodedVideo table, \n   1. we can persist Master Manifest file which contains links of all other resolution manifest file (called Quality-specific Manifest file).\n   2. The Quality-specific Manifest file has the segments name and file location in correct order.\n   3. So, when app requests the Stream microservice, it just provides the master manifest S3 URL location.\n   4. And the app uses the master manifest URL to talk to CDN and S3. So, basically, app becomes the orchestrator instead of the server\n      and directly talks to CDN, preventing a hop. \n\n5. S3 storage and naming convention for these segments - \n     1. I will select videoId as the bucket name\n     2. This will contain the master manifest file and folders for every resolution \n     3. Say we have 3 resolutions -  1080, 720, 360 \n     4. VideoId/1080/1080_manifest_file (Quality Manifest file)\n     5. Inside 1080 folder, you will have 1080_manifest_file and segments folder which will contain all the segment files.\n     6. The 1080_manifest_file will contain the correct order of segment file names and location which needs to be downloaded.\n\n\n6. Videos of 128GB in size should be uploaded in a resumable manner.\n      a. The App uses AWS SDK to strip the 128 GB into multiple small parts of say 5-10MB and persist the chunk information\n          in its local DB.\n      b. When the App first makes a request to the Upload Service, it let it know how many chunks it has the video divided into.\n      c. This is because, the Upload microservice can create a Video Chunk Metadata in its server to avoid single point of failure\n          if the app crashes or even worse the device is eliminated.\n      d. The Upload microservice will talk to S3 to generate UploadId of the multi-part upload and return the S3 URL for all the \n          chunks.\n      e. The App will start uploading to S3 and then make a PATCH request to update the status of that chunk as Complete.\n      f. Now, if the App crashes and it is unable to recover the data from its local DB, it can request the microservice to \n         provide the chunk metadata of the video Id, proceed to upload the chunk from where it left off and continue uploading.\n      g. Once it is completed, the microservice will ask the S3 to mark the multi-upload part as successful and persist the original\n          S3 URL into the Video Table.\n      h. Then it will trigger CDC via SQS and Lambda to get the video transcoded.\n\n7. How would you design your system to allow users to resume watching a video from where they left off, even if they switch devices?\n      a. Whenever an App starts playing a video, it maintains its current activity in ActiveVideoLocal Table with LastModifedTimestamp and LastSyncedTimestamp\n      b. The app makes a periodic request with N seconds to 'SYNC' microservice to sync the data to the ActiveVideo table in the DB. We can also add triggers such as\n          app switch, app close to make a POST/PATCH request to the SYNC microservice before the app goes out of memory.\n      c. Now, when the user left and came back, the app makes a request to get all the user's activities via the Sync microservice. The microservice query the ActiveVideo\n         table and get the list of videoId and lastSegment played and returns to the app.\n     d. Based on videoID, the microservice will query the Video table and get the metadata so that app can start streaming from the last segment played.\n     e. If the same user is watching the same video from 2 different devices, the 'SYNC' microservice would route the requests to 'Conflict Resolution' Server which will\n         validate if the LastSyncedTimestamp (Local) is equal to LastModifiedTimestamp (server). The first checks gives the microservice confidence that both the requests\n         has edits on the latest copy in the server.\n     f. Post that, it validates whose LastModifiedTimestamp (from ActiveVideoLocal) is higher. If one of the requests wins, it will get persisted in the ActiveVideo Table in the server\n     g. The 2nd request will get rejected but to make sure the App which sends the 2nd request has the latest copy, the 'SYNC' microservice will return the latest copy to the \n         2nd App. The 2nd App should take the responsibility to correct its local DB. Meanwhile, the 1st App will not have to do anything as the server and local copy is same.\n     e. Callout: Since this is not about faster retrieval of data (for which I may think about pre-computed cache for user's faster feed), I am only working to get the requirement\n         functionally correct.\n    \n     \n\n\n        \n     \n",
