    {
      "id": "fWORjoE_wq7MME3fbJtXE",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -333.035016102573,
      "y": -1091.4378822675994,
      "width": 1654.433349609375,
      "height": 2550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4u",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1617397714,
      "version": 9934,
      "versionNonce": 1599732558,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1769011445547,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "File De-Duplication Service\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n   1. Users should be able to upload files\n   2. Users should be able to download files\n   3. The system should not persist duplicate files interest of cost savings.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. The system should be retrieve the recent version of the file uploaded.\n   2. The system should be available all the time.\n   3. The system should be fault-tolerant and should not loose any data\n   4. The system should be scaled to support a TPS of 1K requests/sec.\n   5. The file can range from 5MB to 10GB.\n\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. POST /upload/ --> fileID\n\n{\n    filename\n    filesize\n    author\n    uploadTimestamp\n    fileChunks:[]\n}\n\n2. GET /file/<fileID> \n\n{\n     fileId\n     fileName\n     fileSize\n     Author\n     timestamp\n     fileChunks: []\n}\n\nHigh Level Design -\n\n1. Users should be able to upload files of 5 GB and de-duplicate to save storage savings.\n      a. HTTP payload only supports a payload of 5MB. So, even before an APP makes a POST request to UPLOAD micro-service, it needs to strip the file into smaller chunks\n          in its local Database. The local DB of the user will have a FILE table and the actual file will be present in the user's physical disk.\n       b. Using the strip command, the user can create small chunks of the file of size 5MB or so. The threshold varies but in S3 - you can upload a max of 5 GB at once.\n       c. The smaller chunks will be present in the physical location of the user's drive and we will create File Chunk Metadata table in user's DB. The APP also takes the responsibility\n           of calculating the chunk hash\n       d. The APP initiates a POST call with FILE and FILECHUNKMETADATA  information.The UPLOAD microservice persist the FILE data in the FILE table and for every chunk \n           metadata, it was check if such hash exists in the FILECHUNKMETADATA table. \n                   1. If yes, it fetches the chunkS3Location from that location, persist that information for the given chunk and mark the status as 'COMPLETED'. \n                   2. If no, it would create the S3-presigned URL and persist that information along with status as 'NOT STARTED' \n       e. The microservice returns the list of pre-signed URLs for the chunkid which is not present.\n       f. Why did I persist all the information up hand ?\n             1. This is because if the app crashes and the upload was in progress, the server can provide all the FILE and FILECHUNKMETADATA information and the app\n                  can map the same to chunk's physical location --> Solving the case of resumable upload.\n             2. Here the approach is to de-duplicate file's chunk before persisting the data in the S3 storage. Latency can be increased.\n       g. Once the app receives a list of S3 presigned URL, it updates the status as 'IN-PROGRESS' in its local DB, send a PATCH request to UPLOAD service to update \n           the status as 'IN-PROGRESS'  of FILECHUNKMETADATA and then proceed to upload to S3. Once uploaded to S3,  the app will send another PATCH request to \n           update the status as 'COMPLETE' and the microservice will verify if object exists in that S3 location and then update its status.\n       h. Once the final chunk is uploaded and the APP sends a PATCH request saying that the file has been uploaded successfully, the UPLOAD microservice will mark the \n            status in the FILE table as COMPLETED.\n\n\nIn the above approach, I performed 'De-Duplication' in the customer path. I will also take another approach of de-duplicate asynchronously.\n      1. Assume, when the APP makes a POST call, I would blindly generate S3 pre-signed URLs and return to the user.\n      2. Once the final chunk is uploaded and the APP sends a PATCH request to mark the file upload as complete, the DB will trigger a CDC event\n           which will be consumed by 'De-Duplication' service.\n      3. The service will simply find out the \n           'SELECT chunkId, chunkS3Location, chunkHash FROM FileChunkMetadata WHERE chunkHash IN \n           (SELECT chunkHash FROM FileChunkMetadata GROUPBY chunkHash HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT chunkS3Location) > 1)\n       4. Once you retrieve the chunkS3Location, first update those rows as 'PendingDeDuplication' to true so that if the server crashes\n            a new server spawn can retrieve the in-progress pending de-duplication before fetching new ones from the streams\n       5. Retain 1 chunkS3Location and overwrite all the others with the one retained. Call S3 to delete the files from that location.\n       6. Post that, update the rows with 'PendingDeDuplication' to false\n\n2. Users should be able to download the files.\n      a. When the APP sends a GET request to the DOWNLOAD microservice, the microservice returns the FILES and FILECHUNKMETADATA owned by the user\n           with S3Location.\n      b. The App can persist the information in its own local DB with status as 'NOT STARTED' and starts to stream the chunk from S3 or via CDN\n\n\n3. User modified the file. (LastModifiedTimestamp > LastSyncedTimestamp)\n      a. If the requirement is files cannot be mutated, we will start with a new fileId and repeat the above process. This will be helpful to maintain history of versions.\n      b. In such scenarios, when the APP sends a POST request to create another version of the file, we will repeat the above process and add another row in the MasterFileVersion table.\n          and return the new file Id.\n      c. Here, we can optimize as not all chunks will be modified. Few will get deleted, few will be added newly and few will be actually modified. \n      d. In such situations, we should copy the chunk metadata with their S3 location to the new File ID and then return the list of S3 pre-signed URLS with status as NOT STARTED\n          to the user. \n       e. We can do all of these checking with the APP sends a first POST request indicating to create a new version of the file because LastModifiedTimestamp > LastSyncedTimestamp.\n       f. For the new chunks, we can either do de-duplication in the customer PUT path or asynchronously.\n       g. When the user requests to download the file, we will always retrieve the fileID whose version is the latest and give that fileID.\n       h. Additionally, the user can request an older version to become the latest, in that case, we will return the fileID and delete the newer versions\n\nif the file becomes too hot, it will be a hot shard. Hence, we need replicas around that shard which should be spawned before the hot shard goes down. \nSo, we can have some monitoring where if the heartbeat of the hot shard per minute lowers than a particular warning threshold, spawn the replica and \nlet them sync the data so that load balancers can switch the replica wit the hot shard\n\n\nLet's talk about scaling - \n     1. UPLOAD/DOWNLOAD/DE-DUPLICATION servers are stateless. They have the ability to spawn back and see the pending requests and process.\n     2. The DB can be shared based on fileID but since the TPS is 1K and relationalDB can handle 10K TPS/sec, there is no urgent need to shard.\n       \n     ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "File De-Duplication Service\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n   1. Users should be able to upload files\n   2. Users should be able to download files\n   3. The system should not persist duplicate files interest of cost savings.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. The system should be retrieve the recent version of the file uploaded.\n   2. The system should be available all the time.\n   3. The system should be fault-tolerant and should not loose any data\n   4. The system should be scaled to support a TPS of 1K requests/sec.\n   5. The file can range from 5MB to 10GB.\n\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. POST /upload/ --> fileID\n\n{\n    filename\n    filesize\n    author\n    uploadTimestamp\n    fileChunks:[]\n}\n\n2. GET /file/<fileID> \n\n{\n     fileId\n     fileName\n     fileSize\n     Author\n     timestamp\n     fileChunks: []\n}\n\nHigh Level Design -\n\n1. Users should be able to upload files of 5 GB and de-duplicate to save storage savings.\n      a. HTTP payload only supports a payload of 5MB. So, even before an APP makes a POST request to UPLOAD micro-service, it needs to strip the file into smaller chunks\n          in its local Database. The local DB of the user will have a FILE table and the actual file will be present in the user's physical disk.\n       b. Using the strip command, the user can create small chunks of the file of size 5MB or so. The threshold varies but in S3 - you can upload a max of 5 GB at once.\n       c. The smaller chunks will be present in the physical location of the user's drive and we will create File Chunk Metadata table in user's DB. The APP also takes the responsibility\n           of calculating the chunk hash\n       d. The APP initiates a POST call with FILE and FILECHUNKMETADATA  information.The UPLOAD microservice persist the FILE data in the FILE table and for every chunk \n           metadata, it was check if such hash exists in the FILECHUNKMETADATA table. \n                   1. If yes, it fetches the chunkS3Location from that location, persist that information for the given chunk and mark the status as 'COMPLETED'. \n                   2. If no, it would create the S3-presigned URL and persist that information along with status as 'NOT STARTED' \n       e. The microservice returns the list of pre-signed URLs for the chunkid which is not present.\n       f. Why did I persist all the information up hand ?\n             1. This is because if the app crashes and the upload was in progress, the server can provide all the FILE and FILECHUNKMETADATA information and the app\n                  can map the same to chunk's physical location --> Solving the case of resumable upload.\n             2. Here the approach is to de-duplicate file's chunk before persisting the data in the S3 storage. Latency can be increased.\n       g. Once the app receives a list of S3 presigned URL, it updates the status as 'IN-PROGRESS' in its local DB, send a PATCH request to UPLOAD service to update \n           the status as 'IN-PROGRESS'  of FILECHUNKMETADATA and then proceed to upload to S3. Once uploaded to S3,  the app will send another PATCH request to \n           update the status as 'COMPLETE' and the microservice will verify if object exists in that S3 location and then update its status.\n       h. Once the final chunk is uploaded and the APP sends a PATCH request saying that the file has been uploaded successfully, the UPLOAD microservice will mark the \n            status in the FILE table as COMPLETED.\n\n\nIn the above approach, I performed 'De-Duplication' in the customer path. I will also take another approach of de-duplicate asynchronously.\n      1. Assume, when the APP makes a POST call, I would blindly generate S3 pre-signed URLs and return to the user.\n      2. Once the final chunk is uploaded and the APP sends a PATCH request to mark the file upload as complete, the DB will trigger a CDC event\n           which will be consumed by 'De-Duplication' service.\n      3. The service will simply find out the \n           'SELECT chunkId, chunkS3Location, chunkHash FROM FileChunkMetadata WHERE chunkHash IN \n           (SELECT chunkHash FROM FileChunkMetadata GROUPBY chunkHash HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT chunkS3Location) > 1)\n       4. Once you retrieve the chunkS3Location, first update those rows as 'PendingDeDuplication' to true so that if the server crashes\n            a new server spawn can retrieve the in-progress pending de-duplication before fetching new ones from the streams\n       5. Retain 1 chunkS3Location and overwrite all the others with the one retained. Call S3 to delete the files from that location.\n       6. Post that, update the rows with 'PendingDeDuplication' to false\n\n2. Users should be able to download the files.\n      a. When the APP sends a GET request to the DOWNLOAD microservice, the microservice returns the FILES and FILECHUNKMETADATA owned by the user\n           with S3Location.\n      b. The App can persist the information in its own local DB with status as 'NOT STARTED' and starts to stream the chunk from S3 or via CDN\n\n\n3. User modified the file. (LastModifiedTimestamp > LastSyncedTimestamp)\n      a. If the requirement is files cannot be mutated, we will start with a new fileId and repeat the above process. This will be helpful to maintain history of versions.\n      b. In such scenarios, when the APP sends a POST request to create another version of the file, we will repeat the above process and add another row in the MasterFileVersion table.\n          and return the new file Id.\n      c. Here, we can optimize as not all chunks will be modified. Few will get deleted, few will be added newly and few will be actually modified. \n      d. In such situations, we should copy the chunk metadata with their S3 location to the new File ID and then return the list of S3 pre-signed URLS with status as NOT STARTED\n          to the user. \n       e. We can do all of these checking with the APP sends a first POST request indicating to create a new version of the file because LastModifiedTimestamp > LastSyncedTimestamp.\n       f. For the new chunks, we can either do de-duplication in the customer PUT path or asynchronously.\n       g. When the user requests to download the file, we will always retrieve the fileID whose version is the latest and give that fileID.\n       h. Additionally, the user can request an older version to become the latest, in that case, we will return the fileID and delete the newer versions\n\nif the file becomes too hot, it will be a hot shard. Hence, we need replicas around that shard which should be spawned before the hot shard goes down. \nSo, we can have some monitoring where if the heartbeat of the hot shard per minute lowers than a particular warning threshold, spawn the replica and \nlet them sync the data so that load balancers can switch the replica wit the hot shard\n\n\nLet's talk about scaling - \n     1. UPLOAD/DOWNLOAD/DE-DUPLICATION servers are stateless. They have the ability to spawn back and see the pending requests and process.\n     2. The DB can be shared based on fileID but since the TPS is 1K and relationalDB can handle 10K TPS/sec, there is no urgent need to shard.\n       \n     ",
