      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768977227874,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "https://prachub.com/interview-\nquestions/identify-and-mitigate-deduplication-\nprogram-risks",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "https://prachub.com/interview-questions/identify-and-mitigate-deduplication-program-risks",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "DO7Wt5T8uo1OZb_SnTiW9",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 360.9375,
      "y": -1244.1030523822305,
      "width": 1510.800048828125,
      "height": 2550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5j",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1862036370,
      "version": 7699,
      "versionNonce": 35102418,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1769017320267,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Batched Model Runs\n\nFunctional Requirement -\n   1. User should be able to submit their inference request and get an ID.\n   2. User should receive an update on their request once its processed. \n   3. User should also have the liberty to view the status of their request.\n   4. The request should be run in a GPU Cluster based on priority.\n\nNon-Functional Requirement -\n    1. The system should be highly available\n    2. The system should be able to retrieve status in real time (< 100ms)\n    3. The system should not loose any data and must be fault-tolerant.\n    4. The system should support a high volume of request - 100K request/sec\n    5. The system should respect the SLA of 200ms latency per request\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. POST /requests/ --> requestId and status code\n\n{\n     requestJSON\n     userId\n     priority: HIGH|MEDIUM|LOW\n     maxRunTime\n     callbackType: URI|PUSH-NOTIFICATION\n     callback:\n     timestamp\n}\n\n2. GET /requests/<requestId>\n\n{\n      requestID:\n      requestJSON\n      userID\n      priority\n      maxRunTime\n      callbackType\n      callback\n      status: QUEUED|BATCHED|INPROGRESS|COMPLETED|NOTIFY_IN_PROGRESS|NOTIFY_COMPLETED\n      creationTimestamp\n      lastModifiedTimestamp\n}\n\nHigh Level Design\n\n1. User submits a request\n     a. The rate of volume requests is over 100K, which will bottleneck the DB instantly. Hence, we need a ingestion \n          queue where the user can submit their request via SUBMIT microservice. The depth of the queue would \n          eventually govern the Rate Limiting threshold.\n     b. When a USER makes a POST request, the SUBMIT microservice categorizes the request based on priority\n         and put them on priority-specific Ingestion Queue. Since the Queue is standard SQS and the requests does not\n         need to be ordered, it can dynamically scale.\n     c. An available Request Worker retrieves it from the queue at their own pace and write it to the DB with status as QUEUED.\n     d. Whenever a new insert is called into the DB with status as 'QUEUED', we will use it as a trigger to \n             a. send a notification to the user about their request being created, which will update the DB with status \n                 'NOTIFY_IN_PROGRESS_QUEUED' and  'NOTIFY_COMPLETE_QUEUED'\n             b. For the same trigger, we will write it to priority-specific request queues.\n     e. Architecture for CDC - We will use CDC which will output the records in IMMUTABLE DyanamoDB stream and then \n         we will have an EVENT bridge (similar to SNS) which will have content-based filtering and based on that, \n         we can multiple destinations.\n     f. Once the request reaches BATCH QUEUE, an available Batching worker will poll from the queue and update the \n         DB with status 'BATCHING_IN_PROGRESS'. \n     g. Every Batch worker will have a maximum wait for 100ms or max of 100 requests, post which, it will update the DB\n         with status 'BATCHED' and create a new record in BATCH table.\n             1. we can have P10 of latency as wait time for high-priority queue, P30 for medium and P50 for low.\n     h. We will have another trigger in DB when a new record is inserted into the BATCH table where event bridge will consume\n          the request and route it to BATCH PROCESSING QUEUE (which is also priority-specific)\n     i. Once the request reaches BATCH PROCESSING QUEUE, a set of GPU Cluster workers will poll the queue, update the status\n        in BATCH table as 'IN-PROGRESS' and update the status of request with status INPROGRESS and will start to process.\n     j. Once the processing is complete, it will update the status in BATCH table as 'COMPLETED' and update the status of request \n        with status COMPLETED\n     k. Notification queue will be a destination for every request status updates.\n\n\n2. Users wants to view the status\n     a. User makes a request to to VIEW microservice to retrieve the status of the requestID and the microservice can obtain it from the DB.\n     b. In case, the request is hot, we can cache in Redis as a write-through-mechanism where you write to the DB and then to the Redis.\n     c. Redis can follow LEAST_FREQUENTLY_USED so that the available workers can blindly write it to DB and Redis at the same time.\n     d. The cold ones will get eliminated soon while the hot ones will remain in the Redis.\n\n\nLet's talk about scaling - \n   1. Submit/View/Notification Service/Request Worker Service/Batch Worker specific are stateless and can dynamically scale (horizontally)\n   2. Priority-specific Request Queue need not be ordered. Since we prefer to use SQS, it can dynamically scale to support 100K TPS\n       sharded by requestId.\n   3. I would prefer to have three different DBs - one which store user data (as this is rarely updated). The second and third would be \n       REQUEST and BATCH table which can be sharded based on requestID and batchID.\n    4. The intention to keep them in different database is because if I shard by requestID, Batching Workers and GPU Clusters needs to \n        query multiple DBs to insert or retrieve the batch.\n   5. Following that, EventBridge can also scale horizontally as it is stateless based on requestID\n   6. Priority-specific Batch Queue and Priority-specific Batch Processing Queue can scale horizontally sharded by requestID and batchID \n       and they need not be ordered.\n   7. Priority basically means more consumers to high priority queue and lesser consumers to low-priority queue.\n   8. Notification queue needs to be ordered as we don't want the status update of a request to change order. Hence, we will shard by requestID.\n   9. Since cache can handle 100K TPS, but if required, we can shard it by requestId.\n\n\nTo enforce max_latency per request, we need to be positive whether the request would succeed during the initial POST request. \nIn those situations, whenever we receive a POST request, we will calculate our P90 latency and see if the max latency of the request > P90 or 200ms (which is higher). \nIf not, we will reject it to not entertain any request that might fail and on the other hand, we will work to improve the P90.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Batched Model Runs\n\nFunctional Requirement -\n   1. User should be able to submit their inference request and get an ID.\n   2. User should receive an update on their request once its processed. \n   3. User should also have the liberty to view the status of their request.\n   4. The request should be run in a GPU Cluster based on priority.\n\nNon-Functional Requirement -\n    1. The system should be highly available\n    2. The system should be able to retrieve status in real time (< 100ms)\n    3. The system should not loose any data and must be fault-tolerant.\n    4. The system should support a high volume of request - 100K request/sec\n    5. The system should respect the SLA of 200ms latency per request\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. POST /requests/ --> requestId and status code\n\n{\n     requestJSON\n     userId\n     priority: HIGH|MEDIUM|LOW\n     maxRunTime\n     callbackType: URI|PUSH-NOTIFICATION\n     callback:\n     timestamp\n}\n\n2. GET /requests/<requestId>\n\n{\n      requestID:\n      requestJSON\n      userID\n      priority\n      maxRunTime\n      callbackType\n      callback\n      status: QUEUED|BATCHED|INPROGRESS|COMPLETED|NOTIFY_IN_PROGRESS|NOTIFY_COMPLETED\n      creationTimestamp\n      lastModifiedTimestamp\n}\n\nHigh Level Design\n\n1. User submits a request\n     a. The rate of volume requests is over 100K, which will bottleneck the DB instantly. Hence, we need a ingestion \n          queue where the user can submit their request via SUBMIT microservice. The depth of the queue would \n          eventually govern the Rate Limiting threshold.\n     b. When a USER makes a POST request, the SUBMIT microservice categorizes the request based on priority\n         and put them on priority-specific Ingestion Queue. Since the Queue is standard SQS and the requests does not\n         need to be ordered, it can dynamically scale.\n     c. An available Request Worker retrieves it from the queue at their own pace and write it to the DB with status as QUEUED.\n     d. Whenever a new insert is called into the DB with status as 'QUEUED', we will use it as a trigger to \n             a. send a notification to the user about their request being created, which will update the DB with status \n                 'NOTIFY_IN_PROGRESS_QUEUED' and  'NOTIFY_COMPLETE_QUEUED'\n             b. For the same trigger, we will write it to priority-specific request queues.\n     e. Architecture for CDC - We will use CDC which will output the records in IMMUTABLE DyanamoDB stream and then \n         we will have an EVENT bridge (similar to SNS) which will have content-based filtering and based on that, \n         we can multiple destinations.\n     f. Once the request reaches BATCH QUEUE, an available Batching worker will poll from the queue and update the \n         DB with status 'BATCHING_IN_PROGRESS'. \n     g. Every Batch worker will have a maximum wait for 100ms or max of 100 requests, post which, it will update the DB\n         with status 'BATCHED' and create a new record in BATCH table.\n             1. we can have P10 of latency as wait time for high-priority queue, P30 for medium and P50 for low.\n     h. We will have another trigger in DB when a new record is inserted into the BATCH table where event bridge will consume\n          the request and route it to BATCH PROCESSING QUEUE (which is also priority-specific)\n     i. Once the request reaches BATCH PROCESSING QUEUE, a set of GPU Cluster workers will poll the queue, update the status\n        in BATCH table as 'IN-PROGRESS' and update the status of request with status INPROGRESS and will start to process.\n     j. Once the processing is complete, it will update the status in BATCH table as 'COMPLETED' and update the status of request \n        with status COMPLETED\n     k. Notification queue will be a destination for every request status updates.\n\n\n2. Users wants to view the status\n     a. User makes a request to to VIEW microservice to retrieve the status of the requestID and the microservice can obtain it from the DB.\n     b. In case, the request is hot, we can cache in Redis as a write-through-mechanism where you write to the DB and then to the Redis.\n     c. Redis can follow LEAST_FREQUENTLY_USED so that the available workers can blindly write it to DB and Redis at the same time.\n     d. The cold ones will get eliminated soon while the hot ones will remain in the Redis.\n\n\nLet's talk about scaling - \n   1. Submit/View/Notification Service/Request Worker Service/Batch Worker specific are stateless and can dynamically scale (horizontally)\n   2. Priority-specific Request Queue need not be ordered. Since we prefer to use SQS, it can dynamically scale to support 100K TPS\n       sharded by requestId.\n   3. I would prefer to have three different DBs - one which store user data (as this is rarely updated). The second and third would be \n       REQUEST and BATCH table which can be sharded based on requestID and batchID.\n    4. The intention to keep them in different database is because if I shard by requestID, Batching Workers and GPU Clusters needs to \n        query multiple DBs to insert or retrieve the batch.\n   5. Following that, EventBridge can also scale horizontally as it is stateless based on requestID\n   6. Priority-specific Batch Queue and Priority-specific Batch Processing Queue can scale horizontally sharded by requestID and batchID \n       and they need not be ordered.\n   7. Priority basically means more consumers to high priority queue and lesser consumers to low-priority queue.\n   8. Notification queue needs to be ordered as we don't want the status update of a request to change order. Hence, we will shard by requestID.\n   9. Since cache can handle 100K TPS, but if required, we can shard it by requestId.\n\n\nTo enforce max_latency per request, we need to be positive whether the request would succeed during the initial POST request. \nIn those situations, whenever we receive a POST request, we will calculate our P90 latency and see if the max latency of the request > P90 or 200ms (which is higher). \nIf not, we will reject it to not entertain any request that might fail and on the other hand, we will work to improve the P90.\n",
